<DOC><DOCNO> AP890406-0073 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 0950EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Korea-Spring 2ndLd-Writethru a0428 04-06 0409</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Korea-Spring, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0428,0417</SECOND><HEAD>Protests Continue In Korea After Crackdown On Strike</HEAD><BYLINE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with protests, Roh meeting. No pickup.^By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Workers and radical studentsdemonstrated for the seventh straight day today to protest thepolice assault that broke a strike at South Korea's largestshipyard. At least 12 people were reported arrested.   Government officials said the unrest in Ulsan was becoming ashowdown between authorities and ``labor movement forces,'' andPresident Roh Tae-woo met with security officials to discuss theprotest.   ``The most urgent task facing us now is to safeguard thenation's free democratic system from leftist forces,'' Roh told themeeting at the presidential residence in Seoul.   In Ulsan, 150 miles southwest of the capital, hundreds ofstriking workers hurled rocks and firebombs at police in thestreets around the strike-plagued Hyundai shipyard, news reportssaid. Police responded with tear gas, they said.   The news reports said 2,000 striking workers demonstrated.   In the last two days, about 200 police, workers and citizenswere injured in the street battles, the news agency Yonhap said. Itsaid a house and 38 cars were burned by firebombs thrown bystriking workers.   Protests broke out after police raided the shipyard March 30,arresting 700 workers and ending a strike that had left 400 peopleinjured since Dec. 12. Most of those arrested were released, butformal charges have been filed against 10 union leaders.   About 3,000 police guarded the shipyard. Company officials said60 percent of the shipyard's 19,500 employees reported to work.   Police today arrested about a dozen strikers who attackednon-striking workers on their way to work, Yonhap said. Hundreds ofpolice were deployed around residential areas to protectnon-striking workers, it said.   ``The government's authority is being tested, and we will notback down,'' said a senior government official in Seoul.   The three main opposition parties dispatched investigative teamsto Ulsan today to look into the situation. Before departure, theyurged the government to stop using forceful means and try to settlethe problem through dialogue.   Prosecutor-general Kim Gi-chun today called for stern measuresto stop violent protests and said the government was prepared for a``major showdown'' with leftist groups.   On Wednesday, the government ordered an investigatation of 25leading dissident and labor groups which have either sought contactwith North Korea for talks on national unification or spearheadedanti-government rallies.</TEXT></DOC>